00:02:50.110 --> 00:02:51.410
&gt;&gt; Geoffrey Himes: All right.

00:02:51.410 --> 00:02:52.710
Hello. All right.

00:02:52.710 --> 00:02:54.590
Thanks for coming everybody.

00:02:54.590 --> 00:02:56.070
I'm glad to see so
many people coming out.

00:02:56.070 --> 00:03:00.620
What I want to talk about
first is when we talk

00:03:00.620 --> 00:03:05.420
about popular music history, we
usually think of it being made

00:03:05.420 --> 00:03:08.710
by people who sing
and play instruments.

00:03:08.710 --> 00:03:11.200
But I think one of the
things that's interesting

00:03:11.200 --> 00:03:15.460
about Peter's new book is
how he points out the fact

00:03:15.460 --> 00:03:20.240 position:56%
that non musicians play an important
part in shaping the history

00:03:20.240 --> 00:03:21.940
of popular music, and I was hoping

00:03:21.940 --> 00:03:23.700
that we could start off
having you talk a bit

00:03:23.700 --> 00:03:30.090
about why non musicians are an
important part of this history.

00:03:30.090 --> 00:03:31.390
&gt;&gt; Peter Guralnick:
Well I think Sam --

00:03:31.390 --> 00:03:34.840
Sam actually would have [inaudible]
the title producer didn't exist

00:03:34.840 --> 00:03:37.350
at the time, but he liked
to think of himself more

00:03:37.350 --> 00:03:40.720
as a practicing psychologist.

00:03:40.720 --> 00:03:43.210
But his mission in some
ways was very different

00:03:43.210 --> 00:03:45.360
from let's say the mission
of somebody like Rick Hall

00:03:45.360 --> 00:03:50.220 position:56%
who also very much influenced
recorded music, all kinds of people.

00:03:50.220 --> 00:03:54.820
Willie Mitchell created the
sound that showcased Al Green,

00:03:54.820 --> 00:03:58.650
very different from the Albert
Greene with an E on the end

00:03:58.650 --> 00:04:00.870
who had debuted with Back Up Train.

00:04:00.870 --> 00:04:02.170
Am I feeding back [inaudible]?

00:04:02.170 --> 00:04:05.500
Speak up a little?

00:04:05.500 --> 00:04:06.800
All right.

00:04:06.800 --> 00:04:08.100
I'm going to shout out.

00:04:08.100 --> 00:04:13.600
Somebody like Rick Hall was
looking to create a sound.

00:04:13.600 --> 00:04:14.900
He had a sound mind.

00:04:14.900 --> 00:04:19.650
You could go through any number
of takes to create that sound.

00:04:19.650 --> 00:04:22.200
Sam was looking for the
sound that was in you.

00:04:22.200 --> 00:04:25.360
Sam was looking to bring out of you
what you may or may not know was

00:04:25.360 --> 00:04:27.040
in yourself and to
give you confidence

00:04:27.040 --> 00:04:28.340
and courage to express it.

00:04:28.340 --> 00:04:32.790
And in many ways, it's funny, I may
have mentioned that in the book,

00:04:32.790 --> 00:04:36.360
but I was thinking the
other day that I could just

00:04:36.360 --> 00:04:39.040
as easily have called the
book I Hear America Sing,

00:04:39.040 --> 00:04:41.160
The Emergence of Sam Phillips.

00:04:41.160 --> 00:04:42.710
I mean, that's what it is.

00:04:42.710 --> 00:04:44.010
He heard America singing.

00:04:44.010 --> 00:04:45.780
He heard America singing
[inaudible] birds on the trees

00:04:45.780 --> 00:04:51.140
or could be the wind
out in the country.

00:04:51.140 --> 00:04:52.860
It could be the silence
of the country evening.

00:04:52.860 --> 00:04:54.520
It was that kind of singing --

00:04:54.520 --> 00:04:59.450 position:56%
it was what DeFord Bailey heard that
inspired him to play the harmonica.

00:04:59.450 --> 00:05:00.980
Listened to the sounds of trains.

00:05:00.980 --> 00:05:02.450
Living out in the country.

00:05:02.450 --> 00:05:06.700
DeFord Bailey was the person who
was the first African American

00:05:06.700 --> 00:05:09.990
and for many years the only African
American in the Grand Ole Opry,

00:05:09.990 --> 00:05:11.980
wonderful harmonica player.

00:05:11.980 --> 00:05:14.900
So in some ways, Sam was
the exception, I think,

00:05:14.900 --> 00:05:16.480
to what Geoffrey is talking about.

00:05:16.480 --> 00:05:23.570
Producers like Chips Moman
played a very active role in --

00:05:23.570 --> 00:05:30.530 position:56%
not in inflicting the will but in
looking for something in particular.

00:05:30.530 --> 00:05:34.440
And that is what Sam was --
if you listen to a sampling --

00:05:34.440 --> 00:05:39.410
I mean I put together a
collection with the same title

00:05:39.410 --> 00:05:41.730
as the book on Yep Roc Records.

00:05:41.730 --> 00:05:45.050
You can get it on vinyl,
three LP's and two CD's.

00:05:45.050 --> 00:05:50.450
But it -- for those vinyl
favor -- those who favor vinyl.

00:05:50.450 --> 00:05:53.530
But he had such a range of music.

00:05:53.530 --> 00:05:57.250
The one thing that ties
it together is spontaneity

00:05:57.250 --> 00:05:58.690
and individuality of performing.

00:05:58.690 --> 00:06:01.250
That's what he was looking for
most of all and sort of like

00:06:01.250 --> 00:06:06.410 position:56%
when you talk about Harmonica Frank,
a sort of a medicine show performer

00:06:06.410 --> 00:06:10.100
who played the harmonica
and when he came

00:06:10.100 --> 00:06:12.310
to sing just moved the
harmonica around his mouth.

00:06:12.310 --> 00:06:14.720
He didn't use a bracket
or anything like that.

00:06:14.720 --> 00:06:18.760
And to Sam, Harmonica
Frank was a beautiful hobo,

00:06:18.760 --> 00:06:20.270
and he said, "You're a hobo.

00:06:20.270 --> 00:06:21.570
You have to be inspired.

00:06:21.570 --> 00:06:22.870
You have to be resourceful."

00:06:22.870 --> 00:06:24.280
And that's what he
looked for in music.

00:06:24.280 --> 00:06:26.080
So I don't know if
that's a direct response

00:06:26.080 --> 00:06:28.440
to what Geoffrey said,
but it's my response.

00:06:28.440 --> 00:06:32.090
&gt;&gt; Geoffrey Himes: But the book,

00:06:32.090 --> 00:06:36.470
you talk about all these
profound records that came

00:06:36.470 --> 00:06:41.210
out during these 11 years that
Sam was actively making records.

00:06:41.210 --> 00:06:47.350
Whether it's Howlin' Wolf or
Elvis Presley or Jerry Lee Lewis

00:06:47.350 --> 00:06:50.110
or Charlie Rich or Ike Turner,

00:06:50.110 --> 00:06:54.220
these are all obviously very
talented people, but it seems to be

00:06:54.220 --> 00:06:55.820
in the book you're
making the argument

00:06:55.820 --> 00:06:57.500
that the music they
made was different

00:06:57.500 --> 00:06:59.940
because Sam Phillips
was a collaborator.

00:06:59.940 --> 00:07:01.470
Is that accurate to say?

00:07:01.470 --> 00:07:03.750
Is that fair to say?

00:07:03.750 --> 00:07:05.050
&gt;&gt; Peter Guralnick: You
sound so much better

00:07:05.050 --> 00:07:06.350
than I do on the microphone.

00:07:06.350 --> 00:07:09.370
I don't know.

00:07:09.370 --> 00:07:16.970
We'll see if the fault is
in the mic or if it's in me.

00:07:16.970 --> 00:07:23.440
I suspect it's in me.

00:07:23.440 --> 00:07:24.740
But -- okay.

00:07:24.740 --> 00:07:27.880
See, that's what I needed.

00:07:27.880 --> 00:07:29.700
I needed coaching.

00:07:29.700 --> 00:07:32.520
But it's -- I forget
where we were in this.

00:07:32.520 --> 00:07:33.820
&gt;&gt; Geoffrey Himes: What
difference did it make

00:07:33.820 --> 00:07:35.170
that Sam was a collaborator?

00:07:35.170 --> 00:07:37.540
&gt;&gt; Peter Guralnick: I
think so much of it.

00:07:37.540 --> 00:07:41.540
I don't think Sam knew what
was in each of these artists.

00:07:41.540 --> 00:07:42.840
He saw them as artists.

00:07:42.840 --> 00:07:47.100
He saw them as people who
he sensed -- he believed --

00:07:47.100 --> 00:07:48.460
one of the things Sam believed

00:07:48.460 --> 00:07:51.580
in most strongly was his
ability to read people.

00:07:51.580 --> 00:07:54.340
It was also his ears.

00:07:54.340 --> 00:07:58.300
Those were probably the two
things he prided himself most on.

00:07:58.300 --> 00:08:02.240
But he didn't know
necessarily what each person --

00:08:02.240 --> 00:08:05.230
in the case of Howlin'
Wolf, he knew what he heard.

00:08:05.230 --> 00:08:07.100
It's where the soul
of man never dies.

00:08:07.100 --> 00:08:10.960
In that case, he might as well have
been Alan Lomax or field reporter

00:08:10.960 --> 00:08:14.760
because although what he was trying
to do was to bring out the sound

00:08:14.760 --> 00:08:19.180
of Howlin' Wolf to the maximum
degree that you would be able

00:08:19.180 --> 00:08:21.390
to appreciate it as
he appreciated it

00:08:21.390 --> 00:08:24.580 position:56%
on a record as opposed to in person.

00:08:24.580 --> 00:08:27.890
There, he was simply
trying to record it.

00:08:27.890 --> 00:08:31.240
But when he met Elvis
Presley, he describes him

00:08:31.240 --> 00:08:34.450
as being the most introspective
person whoever came into his studio

00:08:34.450 --> 00:08:36.860
and one of the most insecure.

00:08:36.860 --> 00:08:40.310
And all he simply recognized
the unique talent.

00:08:40.310 --> 00:08:42.020 position:56%
He didn't know what that talent was.

00:08:42.020 --> 00:08:47.750 position:56%
In that case, his genius if you want
to call it that, was the patience,

00:08:47.750 --> 00:08:50.130
and the man not giving to patience

00:08:50.130 --> 00:08:58.530
as his associate assistant
[inaudible] the man not given

00:08:58.530 --> 00:09:00.310
to patience.

00:09:00.310 --> 00:09:03.250 position:56%
Sam showed the most extraordinary
patience, and he was willing to wait

00:09:03.250 --> 00:09:06.650
until he heard emerge this
voice and then he wanted

00:09:06.650 --> 00:09:08.780
to do everything he
could to assist it.

00:09:08.780 --> 00:09:12.150
But it wasn't like he had
a vision for Elvis Presley.

00:09:12.150 --> 00:09:15.140
He just simply -- or that he had
a vision for Little Junior Parker.

00:09:15.140 --> 00:09:19.660
I mean, he was looking for them
to express themselves in a way

00:09:19.660 --> 00:09:24.100
that he sensed they had -- they
were able to express themselves.

00:09:24.100 --> 00:09:25.770
In the case of somebody
like Johnny Cash,

00:09:25.770 --> 00:09:29.260
I think what Geoffrey says is
certainly true in the sense

00:09:29.260 --> 00:09:34.420
that Johnny Cash came in with
[inaudible] blues and recorded it

00:09:34.420 --> 00:09:37.900
at one of his very first sessions
in what amounted to a demo.

00:09:37.900 --> 00:09:40.230
And he's got this kind
of [inaudible] voice

00:09:40.230 --> 00:09:42.610
that you would never
recognize as Johnny Cash.

00:09:42.610 --> 00:09:45.460
He sounds almost like
Marty Robbins singing

00:09:45.460 --> 00:09:47.610
in a higher range than he used to.

00:09:47.610 --> 00:09:51.680
And Sam just didn't
hear the song at all.

00:09:51.680 --> 00:09:54.320 position:56%
Eventually, he came to see the song.

00:09:54.320 --> 00:09:58.260
Sam came to see the song
as a metaphor for the way

00:09:58.260 --> 00:10:00.580
in which we're all in prison,
which is kind of a funny thing.

00:10:00.580 --> 00:10:04.130
Sam was not a poetic person
necessarily, but that was --

00:10:04.130 --> 00:10:07.490
and he sold that to
Johnny -- to John --

00:10:07.490 --> 00:10:12.970
Johnny Cash as being a way in which
the songs communicated to everybody

00:10:12.970 --> 00:10:16.950
and then he got John to
speed up the tempo much

00:10:16.950 --> 00:10:21.950
against Johnny Cash's will and
as he did with I Walk the Line,

00:10:21.950 --> 00:10:24.020
and Johnny Cash said,
"This will never work.

00:10:24.020 --> 00:10:26.300
I'll do it, but we'll
never use it," and walked

00:10:26.300 --> 00:10:28.130
out of the studio convinced
they would never use it.

00:10:28.130 --> 00:10:31.660
When he heard it on the radio,
he said, "Dang, that's good."

00:10:31.660 --> 00:10:34.940
&gt;&gt; Geoffrey Himes: Right, but what
I'm saying is that just as Elvis

00:10:34.940 --> 00:10:39.860 position:56%
and Johnny Cash didn't have a clear
vision of what they were going to do

00:10:39.860 --> 00:10:42.460
and just as Sam didn't have a clear
vision of what they were going

00:10:42.460 --> 00:10:46.530
to do, but it was the fact
that they were working together

00:10:46.530 --> 00:10:48.160
that made a difference.

00:10:48.160 --> 00:10:52.720
They were like both on an
artistic qwest together,

00:10:52.720 --> 00:10:54.230
and neither of them
would have achieved it

00:10:54.230 --> 00:10:56.040
without the other in a sense.

00:10:56.040 --> 00:10:57.340
&gt;&gt; Peter Guralnick: Yeah.

00:10:57.340 --> 00:10:58.640
I guess that's true.

00:10:58.640 --> 00:11:02.140
But the thing was is that Sam
was looking for spontaneity.

00:11:02.140 --> 00:11:03.650
I remember.

00:11:03.650 --> 00:11:05.790
Sam was looking for
spontaneity above all.

00:11:05.790 --> 00:11:09.630
I mean, Jack Kerouac talked
about spontaneous [inaudible].

00:11:09.630 --> 00:11:11.030
That was Sam.

00:11:11.030 --> 00:11:17.080
And it was nurturing spontaneity
and seizing upon the feeling

00:11:17.080 --> 00:11:18.380
as opposed to the perfection.

00:11:18.380 --> 00:11:20.360
I mean, Sam hated the
word perfection.

00:11:20.360 --> 00:11:21.730
He said, "I hate that word.

00:11:21.730 --> 00:11:24.020
It should be banned from
the English language."

00:11:24.020 --> 00:11:27.350
I think what he meant
was that as you seek --

00:11:27.350 --> 00:11:29.330
as you correct all your mistakes,

00:11:29.330 --> 00:11:32.140
as you make everything perfect
you achieve nothing more

00:11:32.140 --> 00:11:33.780
than kind of sterility.

00:11:33.780 --> 00:11:40.210
And so, yeah, he was working with
artists who in almost every case

00:11:40.210 --> 00:11:43.070
from Howlin' Wolf, Mike
Turner to Jerry Lee Lewis,

00:11:43.070 --> 00:11:45.840
Charlie Rich apprised that
same kind of spontaneity.

00:11:45.840 --> 00:11:48.820
And that was what he
nurtured most of all I think.

00:11:48.820 --> 00:11:54.910
But it was not so much that
he had a template or any kind

00:11:54.910 --> 00:11:59.510
of specific approach that would
-- and it just delighted him.

00:11:59.510 --> 00:12:01.540
I mean, for instance,
Harmonica Frank or you listen --

00:12:01.540 --> 00:12:04.890
you probably didn't hear it
coming in, but he listened

00:12:04.890 --> 00:12:07.080
to Joe Hill Louis,
and you think, "God,

00:12:07.080 --> 00:12:08.680
how could anybody ever record it?"

00:12:08.680 --> 00:12:10.820 position:56%
I mean, it's completely out of tune.

00:12:10.820 --> 00:12:14.070
It's -- Sam loved distortion.

00:12:14.070 --> 00:12:16.690
You go right to the edge of
distortion and over the edge.

00:12:16.690 --> 00:12:21.200
And yet there's something about
it that's absolutely both unique

00:12:21.200 --> 00:12:22.500
and compelling.

00:12:22.500 --> 00:12:25.370
And that was what drew Sam
to the music to begi with,

00:12:25.370 --> 00:12:29.040
and I think it's what he tried to
bring out of each of the musicians.

00:12:29.040 --> 00:12:32.100
He didn't want them settling down.

00:12:32.100 --> 00:12:35.580 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Geoffrey Himes: One of the things
you talked about in the book is

00:12:35.580 --> 00:12:39.720
that Sam had this -- did have a
vision in the sense that he grew

00:12:39.720 --> 00:12:46.880
up among poor people in Alabama
who were not paid attention to by

00:12:46.880 --> 00:12:51.690
and large by the cultural
establishment of the 40's.

00:12:51.690 --> 00:12:56.890
And he was convinced that these
poor southerners both black

00:12:56.890 --> 00:13:04.580
and white had something to say
and needed a catalyst or vehicle

00:13:04.580 --> 00:13:10.720
to have it come out, to have it
emerge into the public marketplace

00:13:10.720 --> 00:13:15.380
so to speak and that was
what he was going to do.

00:13:15.380 --> 00:13:16.680
You write about this.

00:13:16.680 --> 00:13:20.530
Even though he didn't have
a specific sonic template

00:13:20.530 --> 00:13:22.960
for these people, he did
have that as a mission.

00:13:22.960 --> 00:13:24.260
Is that right?

00:13:24.260 --> 00:13:25.560
&gt;&gt; Peter Guralnick:
Well, he did, yeah.

00:13:25.560 --> 00:13:29.920 position:56%
But I mean, the thing is is that Sam
and from the age of seven or eight,

00:13:29.920 --> 00:13:32.030
he said to me -- he
said, "Listen to me now."

00:13:32.030 --> 00:13:34.870
I'm talking about an
8 or 9-year-old kid.

00:13:34.870 --> 00:13:39.170
Had a sense of racial
injustice, was struck by the fact.

00:13:39.170 --> 00:13:44.930
He was working in the fields on 323
acre farm that his father rented

00:13:44.930 --> 00:13:46.690
and lost with the depression.

00:13:46.690 --> 00:13:48.710
He was working with black
and white sharecroppers.

